 together? Oh you couldna go. You'd have needed a whole train to have took her away, no it would be terrible, ten in one carriage, no, they - the really - if - if - if they went any holidays - they sort of split up and went and stayed with aunts and uncle
s - in - in other villages and that you know. Not not so far away, maybe down in {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}Kilmarnock{\*\xmlclose} or - or - some of these - going - nearly all in or near - or some places in Ayrshire you know. }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8212307\charrsid8538783 Scattered}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2906979\charrsid8538783  all over Ayrshire, so there's plenty of places to go for hol
idays. But my }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8212307\charrsid8538783 favourite}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2906979\charrsid8538783 
 place to go is Lanark. Oh aye, because - we'd - you - you just had to go over the hill to {\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname place}}{\*\xmlopen\xmlns2{\factoidname City}}Glasgow{\*\xmlclose}{\*\xmlclose}
. I just say over the hill, say about four mile away. But it were - it was easy if you went through the park you see. There was a way b
ack to the village now and again, you see what I mean. Going back to the village now, going back to when I was about seven year old. Well it was all right, you - you just walk - went through the fields and - and - and the road, oh aye, we'll come to that 
a
fter. You see, in the summertime - in the summertime, we - we - we - we went holidays in a way, we'll say now, I'm the eldest in the family - well I would perhaps take three. Two or three away. And I would just say to my mother - see you tonight mum. And 
a
way you would go. And you would go tramping. And the first - farm you came to, no, it maybe the first one, the first one you came to you would get hungry. You just went in and a you said - anything to do today mum? Just got the very job for you, taking aw
a
y the - like - clean - clean a barn, muck a barn we call it. You clean a barn - as - as - that was like clearing out for the thing. And - and then - and then in the afternoon you'd to go in and put all that stuff in the midden you know, it's - it'll take 
y
ou - take the - the barn, the yard up, for them, oh well - we did a wee good job you know. And then you - you went in and you sat down at a big - table inside and oh there was - this is what we liked, we - you could eat what you liked. And - big hunks of 
b
read, like you see now, and the cheeses, cheeses all over you know, and big - big - gallons of - of - of milk. Oh you know the real milk just off the cows you know, just off the cow. All along and maybe you can eat it. You can dig in. Oh - oh we were all 
w
ee gluttons when it came. And then maybe went away - oh you're going, they said. Oh well you're - you're away. Says, well you'll - you'll need to get something, you'll need to take something with you. Oh well, no? I don't think we'll bother. Oh, well I'll
 tell you what I'll do, he }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8212307\charrsid8538783 said}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2906979\charrsid8538783 
, I - I'll give you all a happenny each, and you can go into - I forget her name, it was granny something anyway, you can go into granny's on your road back, and - and you - you can give her a happenny, she'll give you footbal
ls each. A farthing - a farthing they was, a farthing. You could get four chuck balls, chuck kinds they call them, chuck kinds and that time, you'd chuck kinds, and that - that'll keep you going for a wee while. And then - then you - then she would name a
n
other place, where - where you went into - asked her then, if she needed - any assistance. And she'd give you a job. What did you do the last time? You tell her like. Well we're all here a job chopping wood. So you had to do it, chop wood you know what wo
o
d is. Wood. Aye. You'd to chop - chop wood. So - that's how we spent our holidays, we spent eight - eight weeks holidays you had - at the school, well that's how we spent it. Travelling - different parts of Ayrshire. It's - aye, what I mean, there's - we 
didna get any trains or buses, oh no, you had - you'd to use your own - feet to travel from one place to another, but as I say - you were travelling - over - over fields, all the time, and it was all short cuts you were taking.
