\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid8212307\charrsid8538783  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2906979\charrsid8538783 
full days I'm talking about, we're talking about - we went in and girdled them, what we call girdling them. Caught them with our hands. Aye.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid14641693 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2906979\charrsid8538783 That couldn't have been easy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid16601601 JL  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid2906979\charrsid8538783 
Oh no, you'd to be very smart. You'd maybe - you'd maybe see a nice trout and you'd - you - you would know that would come to you you know. If you - if you - if you don't make any noise or don't make a shadow. You just stand like that, an
d it's coming with - coming straight down the stream to you, you see what I mean. Whenever they come into your hand and you felt it was right, you just - ooh - threw it on the bank. You had to throw it right away. You could - you couldn't hold them, you'd
 
no chance of holding them. Throw it on the bank. But what we did use a hook for - as you were talking about, was to get - catch else. Mm. We - we never ate them either, the English people in the village here, they - they - they'd give tuppence - tuppence 
for them. Aye. They used to give us tuppence for them.
