Oh there were plenty of children left out, you see, oh aye. You see, we - we begin now to get amongst the - where - you've children - children are really in their own class, their own age, so we're getting into the 
standard now - where there's children that's not - in their cat - category at all. Backward children. Understand. And they just couldn't, at that time, do anything for them. They just stood there, that's like - we'll say - maybe be a boy - or a girl shall
 
we say maybe a boy in a class, we - we'll just say this way, this don't mean anything, we'll say that - that - a boy and girl was in class one. You see? Today. That class was - tomorrow, we're just - this is - this is months that we're talking about, or y
e
ars, do you understand what I'm saying. They would still be there. And all this - these other ones are away up to - five, six, seven or eight. You understand what I mean. They - they were still there. And of course they were scorned by the others - childr
e
n, you see. The result was that - in - in all these villages - in - I expect it would be in the world, you got them in other - we got them in Glasgow too, they was backward children, in the towns and in the villages, and - they called them softies. Yes. O
h quite openly they called them softies. And - they bore up with that too, they didna seem to resent it in any way. No, because - I think they were so much accustomed to it that - it just became a name to them. Aye. Aye.
